                    <FlowDocument>
                        <Paragraph  Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionTitle}">
                            2.1.8 Understanding Students at Different CEFR Levels
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            The content and objectives of a course (and each lesson) should reflect students' progress in learning English. Two of the most common questions beginner teachers ask are: what should I teach? And how much do my students know already? Here is a brief description of the study time implied by the three broad CEFR levels:
                        </Paragraph>
                        <List>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>
                                    <Bold>Basic:</Bold> Basic level students are those students who have a very limited knowledge of the language. They have only been exposed to the language for a brief period of time. They may have only been in the classroom for up to 120 hours.
                                </Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>
                                    <Bold>Independent:</Bold> Intermediate level students are those students who still have limited knowledge of the language but can communicate fully at a basic level. They have been in a longer learning process. They may have been in the classroom for up to 300 hours.
                                </Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>
                                    <Bold>Proficient:</Bold> Advanced level students are those students who now have knowledge of the language but can still improve certain skills and can always expand their vocabulary. They have been learning the language for a longer period of time. They may have only been in the classroom for up to 500 hours.
                                </Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                        </List>
                    </FlowDocument>
                </RichTextBox>

                <RichTextBox x:Name="mod2part1sect12" Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionText}">
                    <RichTextBox.Effect>
                        <DropShadowEffect BlurRadius="20"  Color="Gray" Direction="315"/>
                    </RichTextBox.Effect>

                    <FlowDocument>
                        <Paragraph  Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionTitle}">
                            2.1.9 The International English Language Testing System (IELTS)
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            While the CEFR is a more widely used metric for labeling levels of foreign language attainment, the International English Language Testing System (IELTS) is also an important measuring tool. IELTS is testing system used to measure only the English language proficiency of non-native English speakers (NNES) and is primarily used for acceptance into programs, such as academic programs at universities, and for immigration to the United Kingdom, Australia, New Zealand, and Canada. While the TOEFL test is more commonly accepted in the United States for academic purposes, the IELTS is accepted by over 3,000 institutions across the United States.
                        </Paragraph>
